{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778260889,"nonce":"l5UyKff67Xy++g86EHq9xcp2CE8=","title":"Capacity-restricted RNN ablation: rank-1 to full GRU under matched ε adversary","message":"Stage 6 in the proposed regulator-coupling / decoupling-chain programme (exploration, not committed). Depends on full-state ε adversary (020a65b) and eval-pipeline audit (4469cae).\n\n**Question.** At what point in the architecture-capacity ladder does decoupling kick in? If Gemini's mechanism is correct, there should be a monotone shift from regulator-like (positive Δv) to tracker-like (near-zero Δv) as recurrent capacity increases.\n\n**Architecture ladder** (all trained under the matched ε adversary from 020a65b):\n1. Static linear feedback (state-only, no time index).\n2. LTV linear regulator (from d448c9d stage-2 variant 1).\n3. LTV linear tracker (from d448c9d stage-2 variant 2).\n4. RNN with rank-1 hidden recurrence.\n5. RNN with rank-r recurrence, r ∈ {2, 4, 8, 16}.\n6. Full GRU (180 hidden).\n\n**Analytical prediction.** A monotone shift from positive Δv (regulator-like) to near-zero Δv (tracker-like) somewhere in the rank-1 to rank-4 range.\n\n**Seed coverage.** Run ≥ 5 seeds per rank; use the bimodal-replicate analysis (see issue TBD — bimodal clustering) as the template for handling distributional outcomes rather than collapsed means. Bimodality at low rank would be especially informative.\n\n**Falsification.** A sudden discontinuity, no shift, or a non-monotone curve all argue against \"smooth gain in expressivity smoothly enables decoupling.\"\n\n**Success criterion.** A clean Δv-vs-rank curve with 5-seed error bars for both C\u0026S and rlrmp regimes.\n\n**Cross-refs.** Plan §3 stage 6. Full-state ε adversary 020a65b. Linear baselines d448c9d. Training-methods coord c99ad9d.","files":null}]}